The only thing I dislike about this article is the Person of Interest being turned into a D-Class at the very end. The narrative could very much do without, and I don't see how the Foundation's solution to this is justified. It skips the  mentality we so often see described (a theme which has proven to be rather useful) and makes the research team rather cruel in their own right. This criticism could perhaps be the result of a headcanon conflict, but the portrayal as it is depicted doesn't convince me.

As well, how would the father's apparition act or behave if he knew his son was locked up in the same kind of facility he was? Doesn't that go against the information gleaned in Addendum 2, about not pissing off the Dead? I don't think Kevin's actions should go unpunished, but I also don't think the way the Foundation handles this is appropriate. Now, I guess it is possible that the D-Class ending is just an extension of the article's theme  but I digress.

Criticisms aside. I think this is decently well-written, and while I can agree with Yossi above that the dialogue needs extra work to sound more realistic, I can sympathise with the characters and story being told. So that's my +1








